rray of issues, including global food security, climate change, sustainable economic development, public service provision and gender inequality. This collection, drawing together research from an interdisciplinary group of scholars and co-operative practitioners, considers the different spheres in which co-operatives are becoming more prominent. Drawing examples from different national and international contexts, the book offers major insights into how co-operation will come to occupy a more central role in social and economic life in the twenty-first century.Mainstreaming co-operation will be of interest to students and academics studying economics, business studies, history, politics and international development, but also to policy makers interested in co-operatives and mutuals as a viable alternative to conventional models of social and economic development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  a2008 financial crisis.  aCo-operative movement.  aEconomic development.  aEconomics.  aGender.  aHistory.  aInternational development.1 aConsidine, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannan, Rowshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHingley, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Vern, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCusker, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Cliff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérotin, Virginie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRawlings, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r